default17.
default&#xa0; 
defaultGlobal energy-related CO2 emissions continue to rise. In 2011 they increased by 3.2%, reaching a 
defaultrecor
defaultd high of 31.2 gigatonnes
default, by far the largest source of global GHG emissions
default. The continued expansion of fossil fuel generating capacity over recent years, despite strong advances in clean energy technologies worldwide, means that fossil fuels will inevit
defaultably play a role in energy generation for many decades to come. 
default18.
default&#xa0; 
defaultCCS offers 
defaultthe potential to reduce
default the emissions associated with this fossil fuel use. A power plant with CCS could reduce CO2 emissions to the atmosphere by approximately 80-90% compared to an equivalent plant without CCS
default. The IEA projects that CCS could contribute 14% of the total emiss
defaultion reductions through to 2050 in their 2°C scenario
default.
default19.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAs is the case in the UK, CCS is currently the only large-scale mitigation option 
defaultthat could potentially
default make deep reductions in global emissions from industrial sectors 
defaultwhich 
defaultrepresent one-fifth of to
defaulttal global CO2 emissions and 
defaultwhich are
default 
defaultprojected to grow over the coming decades. The IEA estimate that almost half (45%) 
defaultof the CO2 captured between 2015 and 2050 
defaultwill need to come from industrial applications and 
defaultconclude 
defaultthat “Failure to utilize CCS tec
defaulthnology in industrial applications poses a significant threat to world capacity to tackle climate change” 
default(
defaultIEA 2013 p8
default)
default. 
default20.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAs long as fossil fuels and carbon-intensive industries play dominant roles in 
defaultthe global economy
default, CCS will be
default a
default critical
default carbon abatement technology
default. It
default i
defaults also a cost effective solution, the IEA estimates that without CCS the cost of meeting a 50% global reduction in CO2 emissions by 2050 will be 70% higher
default. Investing in CCS research, development and innovation now will p
defaultlay an important role in reducing the costs of CCS around the world by developing cheaper and more efficient technologies and components, and contributing to characteri
defaults
defaulting storage sites.
default21.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe benefits of CCS are therefore significant, not just for the UK b
defaultut for also for wider global efforts to prevent dangerous climate change. However, there are a number of barriers which have prevented widespread private sector deployment of the technology to date. 
default22.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe individual components of the 
defaultCCS chain 
defaultuse established technologies
default. For example there is in excess of 6,000km of onshore CO2 pipelines in the USA
default and CO2 has also been safely transported to stores offshore in Norway, with over 1MtCO2 stored per annum in Sleipner
default. There is, however,
default limited experience in full-chain CCS projects 
defaultas there are
default no large scale integrated CCS projects on power stations 
defaultoperational to date (although some are in advanced stages of construction)
default. 
default23.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIntegration of the full chain at commercial scale presents bot
defaulth technical and commercial challenges. For example
default, 
